<subSubSection id="C33B59D66712E064B39DFD89FDF20A6D" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B9E0A5D6712E064B39DFD89FCB00C16" blockId="17.[151,1437,627,1410]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B39DFD89FEFB0DDA" bold="true" box="[151,276,627,653]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
In Europe, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6712E064B294FD89FDFA0DDA" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[414,533,627,653]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Apertochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prasina">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B294FD89FDFA0DDA" box="[414,533,627,653]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">A. prasina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the largest species in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6712E064B056FD8EFC5D0DDA" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[860,946,628,653]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Apertochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prasina">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B056FD8EFC5D0DDA" box="[860,946,628,653]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">prasina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<tableCitation id="C6A33FE66712E064B707FD89FB9E0DDA" box="[1037,1137,627,653]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="11.[150,243,478,505]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="TABLE 1a. Distinguishing features in five of the nine European species of the prasina group." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5E5AD56708E07EB39CFE24FB5A0EAE" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" tableUuid="DF5E5AD56708E07EB39CFE24FB5A0EAE">Table 1a</tableCitation>
). Female wing length can reach 
<quantity id="4CD9A7B86712E064B3D1FD6DFEAF0DE5" box="[219,320,663,690]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="17.5">17.5 mm</quantity>
and was never less than 
<quantity id="4CD9A7B86712E064B150FD6DFD2D0DE5" box="[602,706,663,690]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="15.5">15.5 mm</quantity>
. Wings of males can reach 
<quantity id="4CD9A7B86712E064B0FDFD6DFBA90DE5" box="[1015,1094,663,690]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="16.0">16 mm</quantity>
and were never less than 
<quantity id="4CD9A7B86712E064B661FD6DFF290D81" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="13.5">13.5 mm</quantity>
. This alone excludes most specimens of the other species in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6712E064B081FD46FC0E0D82" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[907,993,700,725]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Apertochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prasina">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B081FD46FC0E0D82" box="[907,993,700,725]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">prasina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6712E064B7A5FD41FACC0D82" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[1199,1315,699,725]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Apertochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prasina">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B7A5FD41FACC0D82" box="[1199,1315,699,725]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">A. prasina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species in the group depositing bundled eggs. The costal crossveins are more than half green (
<figureCitation id="131A16D86712E064B7C6FD25FACE0DAE" box="[1228,1313,735,761]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1978,2002]" captionTargetBox="[170,1416,1123,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-56@10.[170,1416,1123,1954]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 12. Apertochrysa prasina s.s. with less than 40% dark ccv, green face and vertex, and no dorsal marks on the abdomen (female from Agarone, Ticino, Switzerland)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6531324" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6531324/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). The dark portion of the im cell veins is very small, and often the three veins are all pale. All gradate crossveins are usually pale, which otherwise is the case only in furwing males of Ap2.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9E0A5D6712E064B3CDFCB1FB2B0C32" blockId="17.[151,1437,627,1410]" box="[199,1220,843,869]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B3CDFCB1FE220C32" bold="true" box="[199,461,843,869]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">Species redescription:</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="3B4900006712E064B2DEFCB1FB2B0C32" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3763882301" box="[468,1220,843,869]" country="Switzerland" location="Switzerland" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" specimenCount="55" specimenCount-female="31" specimenCount-male="24">
Available live-colored material: 
<specimenCount id="9D27C1D46712E064B034FCB1FC9E0C32" box="[830,881,843,869]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" type="female">31♀</specimenCount>
, 
<specimenCount id="9D27C1D46712E064B077FCB1FC410C32" box="[893,942,843,869]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" type="male">24♂</specimenCount>
(
<collectingCountry id="F3364ACD6712E064B0B7FCB1FBA80C32" box="[957,1095,843,869]" name="Switzerland" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3364ACD6712E064B758FCB1FB530C32" box="[1106,1212,843,869]" name="Germany" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">Germany</collectingCountry>
)
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9E0A5D6712E064B3CDFC8AFD270B36" blockId="17.[151,1437,627,1410]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">
Large lacewing species with grass-green or sometimes bluish-green body coloration. Tips of palps dark brown. Frons, scape and clypeus green. Subantennal sutures always unpigmented. The interantennal spot is roundish or pear-shaped. Black caudal scape dots were found in about 20% of specimens. 22% of specimens exhibited a pair of brown or black dots on vertex. Female forewings 
<quantity id="4CD9A7B86712E064B1CEFC21FC860CA1" box="[708,873,987,1014]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.75" metricValueMin="1.55" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="17.5" valueMin="15.5">15.5–17.5 mm</quantity>
, male forewings 13.5–16.0 mm. Costal crossveins less than 50% dark. All males with furwings, which helps to distinguish them from Ap 
<specimenCount id="9D27C1D46712E064B744FC05FB4F0B4E" box="[1102,1184,1023,1049]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" type="male">3 males</specimenCount>
of similarly large size. The im cell is formed by veins that are less than 12% dark; in 38% they were entirely pale. All gradate crossveins are usually as light as the longitudinal wing veins.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9E0A5D6712E064B3CDFB96FDF20A6D" blockId="17.[151,1437,627,1410]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">
Two pairs of reddish or brown spots (often black in dried specimens) on prothorax. Lateral prothoracic spots mostly brown or black. Dorsal abdomen mostly unmarked, but in 25% of cases there were small reddish-brown or dark brown spots on some of the segments. Most abdominal segments with lateral marks. Ventral side of abdomen pale in females, mostly green in males, with pale setae. Eggs deposited in bundles. About half of the larvae enter an obligatory diapause as second instars, even under long-day conditions. The best way to find 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6712E064B7A9FB01FAF60A42" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[1187,1305,1275,1301]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Apertochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prasina">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B7A9FB01FAF60A42" box="[1187,1305,1275,1301]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">A. prasina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is to sweep 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6712E064B39DFAE5FEB80A6E" box="[151,343,1311,1337]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Corylus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="avellana">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B39DFAE5FEB80A6E" box="[151,343,1311,1337]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">Corylus avellana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(common hazel).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33B59D66712E064B3CDFAB9FBDF0AD6" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9E0A5D6712E064B3CDFAB9FBDF0AD6" blockId="17.[151,1437,627,1410]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B3CDFAB9FE8C0A0A" bold="true" box="[199,355,1347,1373]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">Distribution:</emphasis>
Europe, but the recognition of large size and bundled eggs may extend its known range into Asia. In Europe, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6712E064B21EFA9DFE660AD6" baseAuthorityName="Burmeister" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[276,393,1383,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Apertochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prasina">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6712E064B21EFA9DFE660AD6" box="[276,393,1383,1409]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="78">A. prasina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2666B346712E064B29AFA92FE5B0AD6" box="[400,436,1384,1410]" pageId="17" pageNumber="78" sensu="stricto">s.s.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is more common in northern countries than in the south.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
